WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:07.000
All right. Hi everyone. My name is Ben Arancibia and I'm Director of Data Science at GSK.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:15.000
And there I specialize in enabling the use of R by building tools and working with study teams to integrate R into their workflows.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.000
I have to say it, this is my opinion, it's not my company's.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:26.000
All right. So, The Expanse. It's a cult classic sci-fi show and a series of books.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And it's about how people communicate across vast areas of space to achieve goals.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
And I think a lot about this with my role in building tools.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Communication, similar to in space, is really hard.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
And this might be true for your teams, it might be true for many teams.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:50.000
But I think it's especially true for my team, where we're trying to blend individuals who have a PhD in statistics and R package developers,

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
who are very, very different and have very different skill sets.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:02.000
So, when I was working on R package called Beast, which focuses on Bayesian dynamic borrowing with PhD level statisticians,

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
we often used the same words with different meanings.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
For example, they asked for executable code.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:14.000
So, I thought, oh, a .exe file. No, what they meant was just code that you can run interactively.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Another example in this statement is covariance.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
We need to take into account covariate adjustments for Bayesian dynamic borrowing.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
I have a background in stats, not a PhD level, so I thought I knew what they meant.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
And without knowing it at the time, I had absolutely no idea.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.000
And we're talking about two different definitions and understanding of what covariate adjustments means.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:41.000
So, later on, we talked about these two different things, what we meant, and we had a really good culture of collaboration.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:47.000
So, when these things pop up, you often have people actually looking and asking things like this.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:54.000
So, how do you avoid this?

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:00.000
Setting up your team values at the beginning to really have a focus on that culture of collaboration is crucial.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:05.000
So, setting up values. That sounds really easy, doesn't it?

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:09.000
Yeah, it's not. Unfortunately, it's really, really difficult.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.000
So, it's hard. What do you do?

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
What are your values? What's the right balance of too many or too few?

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:17.000
What should they be?

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:28.000
And these are like really tough questions that need to be discussed and decided upon so you can use them when you have those tough questions or you have those kind of obstacles pop up.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
Here are the five values that we established at the beginning of the BEAST package.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
My favorite is radical transparency.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:40.000
Basically, it's a way to be constructive about how to answer tough questions.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:43.000
And it's how you make the best data products, in my opinion.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
How we use these values is we would often reference them in conversations.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
So, like in the spirit of radical transparency, I think we should do a different approach.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Or, in the spirit of trust, you make the decision since it's your area of expertise.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:03.000
And that's really crucial, especially when you're trying to blend skill sets with PhD statisticians and R package developers.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:09.000
So, once you figure out the values as a team, you can go from asking things like, what?

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:14.000
To this.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.000
And that's it. That's what I wanted to talk about, values.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:19.000
So, if you'd like to know more, come talk to me.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:20.000
Shoot me a message on LinkedIn.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Or check out BEAST, which is open source.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
If you're really into Bayesian dynamic borrowing, which I realize is very niche.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.000
But that's the package I reference.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:31.000
It's where we try to implement these values.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
And I'm really proud of this data product that we're able to let everyone use.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:36.000
So, thank you.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Thank you.

